    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3839739107" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3839739107" />
    <a title="Caterina Pierre" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11371828-caterina-pierre"><img alt="Caterina Pierre" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1343522761p2/11371828.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3839739107?book_show_action=true">Mar 06, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Caterina Pierre" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Caterina Pierre" href="/user/show/11371828-caterina-pierre">Caterina Pierre</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback 9782253007296" href="/book/show/817077.Paul_et_Virginie">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3839739107" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6333415031222911203">Bernard de Saint-Pierre’s 1787 novel Paul et Virginie has been on my reading list for many years, ever since I fell in love with P.A. Cot’s painting “The Storm” at the Metropolitan Museum of Art, a painting long believed to be based on a scene in the novel. I recently had the chance to read it in French with a French book club, as well as with another friend outside of the club who read it along with me. Going into it and having read no analysis of it beforehand, I expected a delicious sexy romp</span>
  <span id="freeText6333415031222911203" style="display:none">Bernard de Saint-Pierre’s 1787 novel Paul et Virginie has been on my reading list for many years, ever since I fell in love with P.A. Cot’s painting “The Storm” at the Metropolitan Museum of Art, a painting long believed to be based on a scene in the novel. I recently had the chance to read it in French with a French book club, as well as with another friend outside of the club who read it along with me. Going into it and having read no analysis of it beforehand, I expected a delicious sexy romp a la The Blue Lagoon (which was based on Paul et Virginie). The book is nothing of the sort. The story is mostly narrated by an old man who was the neighbor of Paul and Virginie’s family twenty years earlier. He’s telling the story to a visitor to the Island, which is this: two children are born on the Île de France, now Mauritius, near the Indian Ocean. Their mothers are single: Paul’s mother Marguerite, was promised marriage by her lover but when she is found to be pregnant, she is deserted; Virginie’s mother, Madame de la Tour, is from the aristocratic class. Her husband dies on a slave-buying mission and leaves Madame de la Tour pregnant on the island. The two women find each other, befriend each other, and, being in similar circumstances, decide to work together to help each other and raise their children. They have two slaves, Domingue and Marie, who are married, and who are treated as part of the family. The issue of slavery is a reoccurring theme in the novel, for example the juxtaposition between treating slaves well versus having slaves so badly treated they escape their masters; and also that one can be a slave to money and status. Some readers might be put off by the nonchalant way in which slavery is discussed, but remember that slavery was a reality in 1787 when the book was written. The children are raised almost as brother and sister, but also remember that they are not, so eventually they will reach an age where they will fall in love with each other. It’s a perfect story for quite a good piece of the novel: the island is an idyllic paradise that provides them with all of their needs, and the children are uncorrupted by modern society. Virginie in particular is a model of virtue and grace. The children are also a bit clueless: at one point they meet a fugitive slave, whom they feed and return to the master. There is no thought between them that maybe not everyone treats their slaves the way Domingue and Marie are treated back at their home. All goes well for this family until Madame de la Tour gets the bright idea to write to an aunt with money back in France. It’s never clear why she wants to get mixed up with a family who rejected her after she left with her husband to the Island. But Madame de la Tour, unlike the children, has been corrupted because she was raised in (what Saint-Pierre suggests is) a society that cares only about birthright, money, and status. She’d like to secure some money for Virginie, but for what purpose it isn’t clear immediately, because they don’t need money really on the island. At first she’s rejected by her aunt; then the aunt writes that she is sending for Virginie to be educated in France proper and to be married off to some man, likely with money and titles. Once Virginie is gone, Paul falls to pieces; the idyllic paradise he experienced is gone. Though the land and the beauty of it is still there, without Virginie to experience it with, all is lost. When Virginie sends Paul some seeds from Europe to plant on the island and they do not grow there, the reader immediately knows that disaster lurks in the background.<br />The soul of the second half of the book is the idea that Virginie has been sent into the belly of the beast. Saint-Pierre establishes that French society is corrupt; that the land and nature gives us everything we need if we let it; and that a single decision (which I think begins with Mme de la Tour’s decision to re-engage with her aunt) can have disastrous consequences. Saint-Pierre tackles issues of the First, Second, and Third Estates that made up French society at the time; corruption through money and greed; as well as topics like slavery, arranged marriages, and even vegetarianism. For a book written before the French Revolution, it is an avant-garde powerhouse. The second half of the book, from Virginie’s departure until the denouement, is a deeply felt emotional rollercoaster. It is clear why the book is still in print (with a brand new French edition published in 2020) and why its still important to consider a world where virtue, kindness, and nature are at the forefront, and where the desire for money and status are ultimately worthless when compared to simpler pleasures and virtues, like the cultivation of nature and natural love.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6333415031222911203" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


