<div id="review_2420943435" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2420943435" />
    <a title="Belle Vilers" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/25125527-belle-vilers"><img alt="Belle Vilers" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1393396350p2/25125527.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2420943435?book_show_action=true">Jun 19, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Belle Vilers" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Belle Vilers" href="/user/show/25125527-belle-vilers">Belle Vilers</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780809595136" href="/book/show/14950455-paul-and-virginia-by-bernardin-de-saint-pierre-fiction-literary">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2420943435" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10877040175399420051">&quot;there will be a day of reckoning, where the lava cleanses the earth of evil For you cannot control the power of NATURE!&quot;- Maury, the hormone monster (insert meme from big mouth, ever watch that show? its pretty good) Anyways, I guess in this case, its a hurricane and the ocean killing the virtuous within society. For once you have &quot;fallen&quot; you cannot become innocent again.<br/><br/>My only remarks is about the ending. Particularly on the speech in which the hermit gave Paul in order to comfort him after </span>
  <span id="freeText10877040175399420051" style="display:none">"there will be a day of reckoning, where the lava cleanses the earth of evil For you cannot control the power of NATURE!"- Maury, the hormone monster (insert meme from big mouth, ever watch that show? its pretty good) Anyways, I guess in this case, its a hurricane and the ocean killing the virtuous within society. For once you have "fallen" you cannot become innocent again.<br /><br />My only remarks is about the ending. Particularly on the speech in which the hermit gave Paul in order to comfort him after Virginias death. I find it interesting how, the only way to stay virtuous is through death. For Paul to be happy because Virginia is dead and happy without suffer is such a societal norm; something we convince ourselves in order to continue living.<br />Yet, there is a void for Paul as he is still living and suffering. So what to make of this story? is it making fun of norms? or universally acknowledging the fact that humans are just as part of nature as a worker ant?<br />I dont think there any answers to this, because it is a human experience resolution. You cant be virtuous, and have great ambitions without that fall, or dying a little inside. So, thats just as it is. <br />However, I love the emphasis in which the hermit tells Paul to take comfort in literature, as I think stories gives us some sort of togetherness in our own anxieties and fears. And it ties in together at the end, in which the traveler and the hermit are crying together at the end of the story, but emphasis on the that TOGETHERNESS in mutual understanding "through tears". </span>
  <a data-text-id="10877040175399420051" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


