<div id="review_2020384362" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2020384362" />
    <a title="Sara" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/851558-sara"><img alt="Sara" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1201661009p2/851558.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2020384362?book_show_action=true">Jun 05, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sara" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sara" href="/user/show/851558-sara">Sara</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2020384362" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9884225438200728704">Magnifique! I read the English version because I wanted the backstory of one of my favorite paintings at the Met: &quot;The Storm&quot; by Pierre Auguste Cot. It is very sweet, innocent and at the same time profound, philosophical tale of Paul and Virginia. They are a young man and woman who have grown up together since infancy due to the misfortunes of their single mothers and their subsequent friendship. The mothers build side by side cabins on a beautiful plot of land in Mauritius and live a peaceful e</span>
  <span id="freeText9884225438200728704" style="display:none">Magnifique! I read the English version because I wanted the backstory of one of my favorite paintings at the Met: "The Storm" by Pierre Auguste Cot. It is very sweet, innocent and at the same time profound, philosophical tale of Paul and Virginia. They are a young man and woman who have grown up together since infancy due to the misfortunes of their single mothers and their subsequent friendship. The mothers build side by side cabins on a beautiful plot of land in Mauritius and live a peaceful existence with their respective slaves. Paul and Virginia love each other as brother and sister but grow up and Virginia starts to have new feelings for him which are confusing. She has an opportunity to seek out the wealth of her great aunt who disowned Virginia's mother. Her reasoning is to use this money to benefit the church and those in need on the island. The story continues but to tell more would reveal spoilers. The book, like the painting, is part of the Romantic movement of the 1700's in France- beautifully written with love of nature as a predominant theme. </span>
  <a data-text-id="9884225438200728704" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


