<div id="review_3979515761" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3979515761" />
    <a title="Daniel Cradler" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/72679195-daniel-cradler"><img alt="Daniel Cradler" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1598025212p2/72679195.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3979515761?book_show_action=true">May 12, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Daniel Cradler" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Daniel Cradler" href="/user/show/72679195-daniel-cradler">Daniel Cradler</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/19478137-paul-et-virginie-english">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3979515761" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1025758405385813495">I decided to read this novel after finding it referred to in three different journals written by seafarers who visited Mauritius in the early 1800&apos;s. It seems it was wildly popular in Europe at the time and most everyone had read it. Bernardin uses an over-the-top romantic plot as a framework to expound on his love of nature and distaste for pre-revolutionary French society. Though it is heavy on descriptions of Mauritius&apos; natural scenery (which are questionable in their accuracy according to so</span>
  <span id="freeText1025758405385813495" style="display:none">I decided to read this novel after finding it referred to in three different journals written by seafarers who visited Mauritius in the early 1800's. It seems it was wildly popular in Europe at the time and most everyone had read it. Bernardin uses an over-the-top romantic plot as a framework to expound on his love of nature and distaste for pre-revolutionary French society. Though it is heavy on descriptions of Mauritius' natural scenery (which are questionable in their accuracy according to some journal writers), this book is a quick read and it's fascinating how many of the author's critiques of social structure still ring true today. One could imagine him being some kind of hipster urban farmer in today's world. </span>
  <a data-text-id="1025758405385813495" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


